				<h2>Archaeology in the Classroom</h2>

				<p>Over the past year we have developed a series of archaeology workshops that complement and integrate with the teaching curriculum. Our workshops can last from one hour to all day, incorporating visual presentations, hands-on interaction with genuine and replica artefacts and assessing the lives of ancient people through careful examination of the material they left behind.</p>

		        <hr />

				<p>Teachers can tailor each workshop to suit the needs of their students.</p>

				<p>Here is a list of the activities we can organise:</p>
				<ul id="classroom-list">
					<li>Identifying locations for the establishment of settlements using local area maps.</li>
					<li>Stratigraphy puzzles.</li>
					<li>What would you look like to an archaeologist in 1,000 years?</li>
					<li>Using everyday rubbish to examine the lives of individuals.</li>
					<li>Dissecting ‘poo’ to find out about ancient diet.</li>
					<li>Artefact recording.</li>
					<li>Creating timelines in the classroom.</li>
					<li>Mesolithic cave painting.</li>
					<li>Learning about the ancient boardgame,  Brandubh.</li>
					<li>The many uses of flint.</li>
					<li>Artefact identification and discussion.</li>
					<li>Designing and making your own coins.</li>
					<li>Show and tell: students bring in items they consider to be ancient for discussion.</li>
					<li>How prehistoric pottery was made and decorated.</li>
				</ul>

